# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
C++ STL makes such question so easy. Use iota to create a char array.
Then use next_permutation k-1 times to find the answer!

next_permutation takes $O(n)$ time to find the next permutation.

The second method does not use next_permutation, but calculates the permutations by successively using divisions over factorials. 

For fast performance, the C++ set (ordered set) is used  A recurive version and  an iterative version are provided. Both of them beat 100% with runtime 0 ms!

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
[Please turn on English if necessary]
[https://youtu.be/D__GqhWbfQQ?si=b49DiSKWli7U-2UV](https://youtu.be/D__GqhWbfQQ?si=b49DiSKWli7U-2UV)
# Why using set not array?
Because in the code, it is necessary to erase elements from container in the middle. If array is used, the time for it is $O(n)$ which is too costly. An erase and an insert cost $O(\log n)$, it is the right data structure for implementation.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n \log n)$$ for 2nd and 3rd solutions
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$
# Code using next_permutation which is slow but accepted
```
class Solution {
public:
    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        vector<char> S(n);
        iota(S.begin(), S.end(), '1');
        for(int i=1; i<k; i++)
           next_permutation(S.begin(), S.end()); 
        return string(S.begin(), S.end());
    }
};
```
# Code computing the permutations by successively using divisions over factorials beats 100% with runtime 0 ms
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> factorial;
    string Permutation(set<int>& nums, int n, int k) {
        if (n == 1) 
            return to_string(*nums.begin());

        int index =k/ factorial[n-1];
        k %= factorial[n-1];

        auto it = nums.begin();
        advance(it, index); // Move iterator to the index
        int num = *it;
        nums.erase(it);

        return to_string(num) + Permutation(nums, n-1, k);
    }

    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        factorial.assign(n, 1);
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            factorial[i]= i*factorial[i-1];
        }

        set<int> nums;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            nums.insert(i);
        }
        --k; // Adjust k to 0-based index
        return Permutation(nums, n, k);
    }
};

```
# Code for iterative version
```
class Solution {
public:
    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {

        set<int> nums;
        vector<int> factorial(n+1, 1);

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            nums.insert(i);
            factorial[i] = i*factorial[i-1];
        }

        --k; // Adjust k to 0-based index

        string perm;
        for (int i=n; i >= 1; i--) {
            int index = k/factorial[i-1];
            k%= factorial[i-1];
            auto it=nums.begin();
            advance(it, index); // Move iterator to the index
            perm+= to_string(*it);
            nums.erase(it);//O(log n) time
        }
        return perm;
    }
};

```
