solutions.content:
The base idea is that the first character can be found knowing that it is repeated `(n - 1)!` times.

If you have `1234` as your own base, for example, all the permutations starting with, say, `2`, are going to be like this:

`2134`
`2143`
`2314`
`2341`
`2413`
`2431`

Since you can indeed only permutate remaining `n - 1` elements `(n - 1)!` times.

So you will have 6 permutations startins with `1`, 6 starting with `2` and so on.

Once you get the first character, the problem is just a replica of itself (being careful to remove the first character you just found, in the above case would be `2`) and considering a new `k` as the remainder of the division by `(n - 1)!`, so, in my code: `k %= fact[n]`.

Rinse and repeat until you either have no more characters left to assign (in my code it would have been `!chars.size()`) or slightly more efficient to compute at each loop, until `n`).

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    // we know 1 <= n <= 9 - so storing pre-computed results is fine
    vector<int> fact = {1, 1, 2, 6, 24, 120, 720, 5040, 40320, 362880};

    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        string res = "";
        vector<char> chars(n);
        int pos;
        k--; //adjusting for 1 based counting
		// prepopulating our base vector of available chars
        for (int i = 1; i <= n;) chars[i++ - 1] = '0' + i;
        while (n) {
            pos = k / fact[--n];
            res += chars[pos];
            chars.erase(begin(chars) + pos);
            k %= fact[n];
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

It might be fun also to turn it into recursive, although I guess it will take more memory for no significant gain; also, 
I am wondering if I can avoid having a vector at all - probably so, but would complicate my logic significantly.

