1. Given n digits there will be total of `(n * (n-1) * ... * 2 * 1)` different permutations. - the 1st digit you have `n` options, 2nd digit you have `n-1`, ... last digit you only have `1` option.
2. Your choices to pick different number at each digit will form different groups of permutations. Example: Your choice for the `n` different number at the `1st` digit will result in `n` groups of permutations, start with `1` ~ `n`. and each group will contain `(n-1) * ... * 2 * 1)` permutations which can be further divided into n-1 groups, and so on...
3. Given `0-based` sequence index `k`, what is the 1st `number` of the `k`th permutation depend on which `group` it is in, and this can be calculated by `k / $group_size`, which is `k / ((n-1)*...*2*1)`, and within that group, its index will be `k % ((n-1)*...*2*1)`, and `k` should be updated as that.
4. Once 1st number is determined, the 2nd number can be determined by which sub-group it belongs to within the first level group, which again can be calculated by `k / $group_size`.
```
class Solution {
public:
    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        string digits = "123456789"; // digits pool, as numbers being picked 1 by 1, options will be reduced, pool will shrink
        /* Calculate the weight as n factorial, it is actaully the weight on the n+1 th digit */
        int weight = 1; // total number of permutations will be (n*...*2*1)
        for (int d = 1; d <= n; d++) weight *= d; // k options for kth digit
        --k %= weight; // use 0-based k, and module to weight;
        string s(n, '\0');
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            weight /= (n - i);  // digit[0] have n options, digit[i] have n - i options
            int d = k / weight; // calculate digit id
            s[i] = digits[d];
            digits.erase(d, 1); // reduce digit from the pool, for it can only be used 1 time
            k %= weight;
        }

        return s;
    }
};
```

