This is a classic math problem.
consider n =3
1. Number of permuttions of length n (n digits here) are n!. eg: 3!=6
2. It can also be written as n*(n-1)!   eg: 3*(3-1)! = 6
3. So there are n groups with (n-1)! permutations in each group.
 eg: for n=3 there will be 3 groups with ((n-1)! which is) 2 permutation in each group 
 group1 = {123, 132}
 group2 = {213, 231}
 group3 = {312, 321}
So the basic math is to identify the group which will contain Kth permutation and then select the element at that index and then repeat the steps for lesser n and k

for n = 3, our first permutaion is "123" and k=3 our answer will be 213. how?

frist pass - 
k = k/fact(n-1)! which is ceil(3/2!) -> 2 so select index 2 (0 based) from the first string which is "2";
now k = k%fact(n-1) which is 3%2! -> 1
n-- which is 2
now our string is = "13", we removed 2

second pass - 
k = k/(n-1)! --> 1/1! --> 1 --> index1 in str--> "1"
k = k%(n-1)! --> 1%1 --> 0(in this case we set k to be (n-1)! which is 1)
n-- which is 1
now our string is "3"since we removed 1

third pass:
k = k = k/(n-1)! --> 1/0! --> 1 --> index1 in str--> "3"

so one by one we removed 3,2 and 1 from our initial sequence.

