First thing to say, It was quite a long time when I first solved this. 
And when I reviewed this question and saw my solution, I want to share it.
But I'm not completely sure if it wasn't "copied" (or the idea wasn't copied) from other place.
If it is, please let me know.

**Jump back to the solution.** The idea is very simple.
Let's say we are working on the first element of the answer.
For the permutation from small to large, clearly the first element will change from **'1'** to **'n'**.

How much steps of permutation will it be between every first element changing?
Obviously it's the number of permutations of the rest of the sequence.
The number will be **(n - 1)!**.
So all we need to do is to calculate **k / (n - 1)!** and we'll get the index of **'1'** to **'n'** for the first element.

Then with the same logic, we work on the second element.
The **k** now will become  **k % (n - 1)!** from the last round. The available characters to choose will be **'1'** to **'n'** and erase already used ones.


```
string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
	vector<char> v; // store the available characters we can use
	int p = 1;
	for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
		p *= i;
		v.push_back('0' + i);
	}

	string ans = "";
	k--;
	for(int i = n; i > 0; i--){
		p /= i;
		ans.push_back(v[k / p]);
		v.erase(v.begin() + k / p);
		k %= p;
	}
	return ans;
}
```

