# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The Intuition is to traverse the linkedlist and return the node where the two list join and if there is no joining of the list we simply return NULL

# Brute force 
We will point to a node in list 1 and check it with all the node of the list2 and if we get the same node then return that node or else return NULL;

**Time complexity:** **O(n*m)**
n =length of the list 1.
m=length of the list2.
**Space complexity:**  **O(1)**

# Hashing 
Store all the node of the list1 and list2 in hash table and when the two node have same key then return that node.

**Time complexity:** **O(n+m)**
**Space complexity:**  **O(n+m)**

# Optimal 1

1. Find the length of the first list and then the length of second list.
2. Move the head of the longer length linkedlist till the difference of the length of two list.
3. After that move both the head simultaneously and return the value where they collide.

**Code**
```
public class Solution {
    public ListNode getIntersectionNode(ListNode headA, ListNode headB) {
        int n1=0,n2=0;
        ListNode temp=headA;
        while(temp!=null){
            n1++;   //count the length of the list 1
            temp=temp.next;
        }
        temp=headB;
        while(temp!=null){
            n2++;   //count the length of the list2
            temp=temp.next;
        }
        ListNode larger=headA;
        ListNode smaller=headB;
        if(n1<n2){      //if A is not the larger list then swap
            ListNode p=larger;
            larger=smaller;     
            smaller=p;
        }
        int diff=Math.abs(n1-n2);
        for(int i=0;i<diff;i++){
            larger=larger.next;
        }
         if(larger==smaller){
                return larger;
            }
        while(larger!=null&&smaller!=null){
            larger=larger.next;
            smaller=smaller.next;
            if(larger==smaller){
                return larger;
            }

        }
        return null;
    }
}
```
**Time complexity:** **O(n+m)**
**Space complexity:**  **O(1)**

This the optimal code However the line of code is a little bit larger.
# Optimal 2
1. Traverse the list1 and list 2 
2. The moment one of the list reaches the null then assign it to the head of other list.
3. Again traverse both the list and if the second list reaches the list then assign it to the head1.
4. Traverse the list till it collide and return the collide node .

